1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:13,016
Sherlock Holmes is an imaginary private detective created by British writer Arthur Conan Doyle in the late 1880s.

2
00:00:13,016 --> 00:00:21,459
Doyle’s stories about the detective have been turned into movies and television shows.

3
00:00:21,459 --> 00:00:27,501
One of Sherlock Holmes’ great skills is a powerful memory.

4
00:00:27,501 --> 00:00:39,464
In a recent BBC television series, the character uses a memory technique called a “mind palace” or “memory palace.”

5
00:00:39,464 --> 00:00:52,245
On one show, for example, Holmes has been severely wounded in a shooting and retreats into his mind to search for ways to survive.

6
00:00:52,245 --> 00:00:59,296
He visits rooms in his mind palace, looking for helpful memories.

7
00:00:59,296 --> 00:01:07,915
In one room, he finds his childhood dog, and the memory helps calm the detective.

8
00:01:07,915 --> 00:01:14,352
The memory palace idea was not a BBC creation.

9
00:01:14,352 --> 00:01:20,685
The method for remembering has existed for thousands of years.

10
00:01:20,685 --> 00:01:30,499
Many language educators today teach their students how to use the method to improve their language skills.

11
00:01:30,499 --> 00:01:34,357
But what exactly is a memory palace?

12
00:01:34,357 --> 00:01:42,515
It is a real structure, such as a home or building, that you can picture in your head.

13
00:01:42,515 --> 00:01:50,211
You then imagine placing things you want to remember inside the structure.

14
00:01:50,211 --> 00:02:00,915
You can use a memory palace to remember words, phrases, facts, or even the order of events.

15
00:02:00,915 --> 00:02:10,376
If you can see the inside of a house or building in your mind, you can make your own memory palace.

16
00:02:10,376 --> 00:02:15,355
On today’s Education Tips, we will show you how.

17
00:02:15,355 --> 00:02:21,493
Start with a list of words or phrases that you want to remember.

18
00:02:21,493 --> 00:02:35,467
Then, close your eyes and choose a physical space that you know well, such as your home, a school you attended, or a current or former workplace.

19
00:02:35,467 --> 00:02:42,643
If your chosen space has only one or two rooms, do not worry.

20
00:02:42,643 --> 00:02:54,037
You can also use things like doors, passageways, steps or other permanent places along the physical path.

21
00:02:54,037 --> 00:03:04,107
The next step is to imagine walking through the space using the path that you would normally take through it.

22
00:03:04,107 --> 00:03:13,339
As you walk through, put objects that you want to remember at specific places along the path.

23
00:03:13,339 --> 00:03:21,005
Leave the objects there to pick up later when you visit your memory palace.

24
00:03:21,005 --> 00:03:35,144
Now, let’s try this technique by using six ingredients for a pizza: flour, water, dry yeast, tomato sauce, cheese and basil.

25
00:03:35,144 --> 00:03:39,045
Close your eyes and picture a home.

26
00:03:39,045 --> 00:03:47,112
First, you open the front door and see a bag of flour on the floor.

27
00:03:47,112 --> 00:03:53,213
The bag is broken and some of the flour has spilled.

28
00:03:53,213 --> 00:04:00,467
You are worried that you might slip, so you carefully step over the area.

29
00:04:00,467 --> 00:04:05,336
Second, you walk into your bedroom.

30
00:04:05,336 --> 00:04:10,035
On top of your bed sits a cup of water.

31
00:04:10,035 --> 00:04:16,323
The cup is shaped like an upside-down piece of pizza.

32
00:04:16,323 --> 00:04:21,840
You think about how funny that is and laugh about it.

33
00:04:21,840 --> 00:04:32,243
Third, as you enter the living room, you see a very large spoon of dry yeast sitting on the sofa.

34
00:04:32,243 --> 00:04:38,064
The spoon is watching a cooking show on television.

35
00:04:38,064 --> 00:04:45,672
Fourth, while standing in the living room, you notice the room has a strange smell to it.

36
00:04:45,672 --> 00:04:52,965
You look above the television and see a block of cheese hanging on the wall.

37
00:04:52,965 --> 00:05:01,269
Fifth, you walk into the kitchen and see two tomatoes chasing each other around the room.

38
00:05:01,269 --> 00:05:07,371
Suddenly, they crash and explode, covering the floor in red.

39
00:05:07,371 --> 00:05:13,621
And sixth, you open the back door and go outside.

40
00:05:13,621 --> 00:05:20,427
There, you see a group of very tall green basil plants.

41
00:05:20,427 --> 00:05:28,179
In a funny voice, the tallest plant says, “Choose me! Choose me!”

42
00:05:28,179 --> 00:05:38,333
Did you notice anything strange about the palace? It was full of extraordinary and humorous imagery.

43
00:05:38,333 --> 00:05:42,355
We will say more about that in a few minutes.

44
00:05:42,355 --> 00:05:48,549
But first, let’s check how well our technique worked.

45
00:05:48,549 --> 00:05:52,059
See if you can answer these questions:

46
00:05:52,059 --> 00:05:59,603
1-What was on the wall above the television?

47
00:05:59,603 --> 00:06:04,888
2-Where were the tomatoes and what were they doing?

48
00:06:04,888 --> 00:06:10,491
3-Which object was sitting on the bed?

49
00:06:10,491 --> 00:06:16,611
4-Where was the yeast and what was it doing?

50
00:06:16,611 --> 00:06:22,992
5-Which ingredient spoke and what did it say?

51
00:06:22,992 --> 00:06:29,411
6-What did you see when you opened the front door?

52
00:06:29,411 --> 00:06:35,528
My guess is that you remembered everything in our memory palace.

53
00:06:35,528 --> 00:06:37,771
That’s good news.

54
00:06:37,771 --> 00:06:44,208
Experts offer some advice for making strong memory palaces.

55
00:06:44,208 --> 00:06:58,987
For instance, if you want to remember a lot of words, memory trainer Anthony Metivier suggests first drawing a simple map of your memory palace.

56
00:06:58,987 --> 00:07:08,107
Then, number the places along your path where you will put the things that you want to remember.

57
00:07:08,107 --> 00:07:13,240
You can put more than one thing in each room or area.

58
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:16,984
Later, you will add the mental imagery.

59
00:07:16,984 --> 00:07:27,888
English teacher James, of the YouTube channel JamesESL English Lessons, has additional advice.

60
00:07:27,888 --> 00:07:37,304
In his video on memory palaces, he says that there are three keys to a strong memory palace.

61
00:07:37,304 --> 00:07:46,109
They are: emotion, movement, and connections between the object and something permanent.

62
00:07:46,109 --> 00:07:57,621
Both he and Metivier say imagining things in a humorous or crazy way improves your ability to remember them.

63
00:07:57,621 --> 00:08:08,216
These experts also agree that connecting images to actions or movement will create lasting memories.

64
00:08:08,216 --> 00:08:15,344
For instance, the tomatoes were chasing each other and the basil spoke.

65
00:08:15,344 --> 00:08:26,331
And finally, teacher James suggests placing the objects next to or on something permanent in your palace.

66
00:08:26,331 --> 00:08:34,989
Beds, sofas, floors, walls, doors – all of these are permanent.

67
00:08:34,989 --> 00:08:40,125
The block of cheese was on the wall, for example.

68
00:08:40,125 --> 00:08:52,293
Now, it’s your turn. Pick a list of English words or phrases that you have trouble remembering and try this method on your own.

69
00:08:52,293 --> 00:08:54,872
Let us know how it goes.

70
00:08:54,872 --> 00:08:56,560
I’m John Russell.

71
00:08:56,560 --> 00:08:59,951
And I’m Alice Bryant.